The Stokes Inlet that lends the park its name offers many recreational activities on the water, in the surf or in the wetland.

The main camping and day area next to the mouth of the inlet is the usual spot but there are a couple other places in the park that are a bit off the beaten track.
The turn off for Stokes inlet Rd is about 80km west of

on the South Coast Hwy. Access to Quaggi Beach is via Farrels Rd, around 70km from Esperance. To get to Fanny Cove, turn off at the 4WD track half way down Farrels Rd, on boundary of a the last farm property. It is about 19km further to Fanny Cove.

value: - The crumbling walls of a pioneer house. On the track to Fanny Cove.
- Five large sheltered sites up in the dunes.  and a long drop toilet. No water or fires. Free to stay. Access by 4WD.
- Camp however you like in the prescribed sites.

- A ramble of campsites behind the dunes in the Banksia trees are suitable for caravans and every other accommodation you could drag in. The crusty looking toilet block is serviceable if the trees are not your thing. An honour box asks for $3 per night if you're the honourable type.

Camping rough outside of the campsites or in parking lots is not permitted.
